data: {"type":"layer1","modelId":"local/apple-fm","model":"Crucible (offline)","text":"## Zod Schema for IPv4 Address Validation\n\n```typescript\nimport { Zod } from 'zod';\n\nconst ipv4Schema: Zod.Schema<IPv4Address> = {\n  name: {\n    type: 'string',\n    required: true,\n  },\n  address: {\n    type: 'string',\n    required: true,\n    pattern: /^(25[0-5]|2[0-4][0-9]|[01]?[0-9][0-9]?)\\.(25[0-5]|2[0-4][0-9]|[01]?[0-9][0-9]?)\\.(25[0-5]|2[0-4][0-9]|[01]?[0-9][0-9]?)\\.(25[0-5]|2[0-4][0-9]|[01]?[0-9][0-9]?)$/,\n  },\n};\n\nexport const validateIPv4Address = (address: string): boolean => {\n  return ipv4Schema.parse(address);\n};\n\nexport interface IPv4Address {\n  name: string;\n  address: string;\n}\n```\n\n## Explanation\n\n- **IPv4 Address Validation**: The schema `ipv4Schema` validates an IPv4 address by ensuring it follows the standard IPv4 address format. The `address` property uses a regular expression to match the pattern `^(25[0-5]|2[0-4][0-9]|[01]?[0-9][0-9]?)\\.(25[0-5]|2[0-4][0-9]|[01]?[0-9][0-9]?)\\.(25[0-5]|2[0-4][0-9]|[01]?[0-9][0-9]?)\\.(25[0-5]|2[0-4][0-9]|[01]?[0-9][0-9]?)$`, which checks for four octets, each ranging from 0 to 255.\n\n- **Schema Usage**: The `validateIPv4Address` function uses the `parse` method of the schema to validate an input string. If the string matches the pattern, it returns `true`, indicating a valid IPv4 address; otherwise, it returns `false`.\n\n- **IPv4 Address Interface**: The `IPv4Address` interface defines the structure of an IPv4 address, containing a `name` and an `address` property.\n\nThis schema provides a clear and concise way to validate IPv4 addresses, ensuring that the input adheres to the standard format.","done":true}

